Good catch. If we hardcode `colour` and `storage` we're locked in. The generic approach would be:

```json
{
  "model": "Galaxy S25",
  "fromPrice": { "amount": "32.00", "currency": "GBP" },
  "optionTypes": [
    { "key": "colour", "values": ["Silver", "Navy"] },
    { "key": "storage", "values": ["128GB", "256GB"] }
  ],
  "variants": [
    {
      "id": "galaxy-s25-128-silver",
      "attributes": [
        { "key": "colour", "value": "Silver" },
        { "key": "storage", "value": "128GB" }
      ],
      "monthlyCharge": { "amount": "32.00", "currency": "GBP" },
      "rrp": { "amount": "768.00", "currency": "GBP" },
      "outOfStock": false
    }
  ]
}
```

- `optionTypes` drives the radio button groups (frontend doesn't need to hardcode "colour" or "storage")
- `variants[].attributes` tells you exactly which combination each variant represents
- Adding a new dimension (e.g. connectivity) is just another entry in both

